---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { site } from '../../data/site.js';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const href = (url) => {
  if (url.startsWith('http')) return url;
  const cleanBase = base.endsWith('/') ? base.slice(0, -1) : base;
  const cleanUrl = url.startsWith('/') ? url : `/${url}`;
  return `${cleanBase}${cleanUrl}`;
};

const title = "Why First-Time Managers Struggle to Give Feedback and How to Fix It";
const description = "Avoiding feedback kills morale faster than giving it. A calm 3-line method for first-time managers to give clear feedback without guilt.";
const topic = "Feedback";
const number = "03";
const longEmbed = null;
const longWatch = null;
const shorts = [];
const related = [
  {
    "title": "How to Delegate Without Micromanaging as a New Manager",
    "slug": "/articles/delegate-without-micromanaging/",
    "topic": "Delegation"
  },
  {
    "title": "How New Managers Can Build Authority Without Being Harsh",
    "slug": "/articles/build-authority-as-new-manager/",
    "topic": "Authority"
  }
];

const bookUrl = href('/books/the-first-30-days-as-a-new-manager/');
const articlesUrl = href('/articles/');
const resourcesUrl = href('/resources/');

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: title,
  description,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
  },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
    url: site.siteUrl,
  },
  mainEntityOfPage: new URL(`${base}articles/feedback-without-killing-morale/`, site.siteUrl).toString(),
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  path={`/articles/feedback-without-killing-morale/`}
  schema={[schema]}
>
  <main class="article-page">
    <nav class="crumbs">
      <a href={articlesUrl}>Articles</a>
      <span>/</span>
      <span>{number}</span>
    </nav>

    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="kicker">{topic}</p>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>{description}</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Read the book</a>
        <a href={resourcesUrl}>Resources</a>
        {longWatch && <a href={longWatch} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Watch video</a>}
      </div>
    </header>

    {longEmbed && (
      <section class="media-block">
        <div class="video-frame long">
          <iframe
            src={longEmbed}
            title={title}
            loading="lazy"
            allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen
          ></iframe>
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <article class="article-body">
      <h1>Why First-Time Managers Struggle to Give Feedback and How to Fix It</h1>
<p>Most first-time managers don&#x27;t avoid feedback because they are nice.</p>
<p>They avoid it because they are afraid of losing the relationship.</p>
<p>You were peers last month. Now you have to tell someone their work was late, or sloppy, or dismissive in a meeting. So you wait. You soften it. You hope they figure it out on their own.</p>
<p>They won&#x27;t. And the delay makes it worse.</p>
<h2>What usually happens</h2>
<p>It happens by week two. Someone misses a deadline. You say nothing in the moment. You tell yourself you&#x27;ll bring it up in their 1:1.</p>
<p>In the 1:1, you spend 20 minutes on project updates. With three minutes left, you say, “Oh, one small thing, try to be a bit more on top of timelines, okay?”</p>
<p>That is not feedback. That is a hint.</p>
<p>Or you do the sandwich: compliment, vague criticism, compliment. The person leaves remembering only the bread. The meat is gone.</p>
<p>The longer you wait, the bigger the conversation feels. By week three, a small miss has become a pattern, and now giving feedback feels like a confrontation.</p>
<h2>Why this becomes a problem</h2>
<p>Performance drifts. If no one corrects early, small misses become standard. Then you have to correct a habit, not a moment. That is ten times harder.</p>
<p>Resentment builds. The rest of the team sees the miss. If you say nothing, they assume you don&#x27;t see it, or you don&#x27;t care. Morale drops faster from ignored problems than from direct feedback.</p>
<p>You lose authority. A manager who won&#x27;t address issues is not kind. They are avoidant. The team can feel the difference.</p>
<p>You explode later. Avoid, avoid, avoid, then snap in a meeting. That is what happens when feedback has no regular outlet.</p>
<h2>The mistake managers make</h2>
<p>The mistake is making feedback a big event.</p>
<p>New managers think feedback needs a perfect moment, the right tone, a private room, and 30 minutes. So it never happens.</p>
<p>Feedback is not an event. It is maintenance. Short. Early. Normal.</p>
<p>The other mistake is overexplaining the feedback, again. Five minutes of context to deliver one sentence. That dilutes it to nothing.</p>
<h2>What to do instead</h2>
<p>Use: Observation. Impact. Next step. Three lines. Done in 60 seconds.</p>
<p><strong>1. Observation. What happened, specifically.</strong> No adjectives. No personality. Just facts. “You missed the client report deadline yesterday. It went out at 6pm instead of noon.”</p>
<p><strong>2. Impact. Why it mattered.</strong> One sentence. “That delayed the client review and I had to explain the gap.”</p>
<p><strong>3. Next step. What changes now.</strong> Clear and actionable. “Next time, send me a flag by 10am if you’re going to be late. Deadline stays noon.”</p>
<p>That’s it. No lecture. No “I know you’re trying hard”. No apology for giving feedback.</p>
<p>Deliver it within 24 hours. In private. Calm voice. Then move on.</p>
<p>If they get defensive, don’t debate. Repeat the next step once. “Understood. Still need the flag by 10am going forward.” Stop.</p>
<h2>Example</h2>
<p><strong>Instead of:</strong> “Hey, you’re doing great overall, really great, I just think maybe, if possible, could we try to be a bit more punctual with reports? No worries at all if not, just a thought!”</p>
<p>The person hears: nothing is wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Say:</strong> “Observation: The report was 6 hours late yesterday. Impact: The client meeting slipped. Next step: Flag me by 10am if you’ll miss noon, every time. Can you do that?”</p>
<p>Clear. Respectful. Done in 45 seconds. The person knows exactly what to fix.</p>
<h2>How to apply this this week</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Give one piece of feedback in the next 24 hours.</strong> Pick the smallest real issue you’ve been avoiding. Use Observation/Impact/Next step.</li>
<li><strong>Never sandwich.</strong> No compliment padding. Start with the observation. It’s kinder to be clear.</li>
<li><strong>Keep it under 90 seconds.</strong> If your feedback takes longer than 90 seconds, you’re overexplaining. Cut it.</li>
<li><strong>Log it.</strong> After each feedback conversation, write one line: who, what, date. This stops you from repeating the same conversation three times without noticing.</li>
<li><strong>Normalize it.</strong> Give positive feedback the same way: Observation/Impact. “You closed that ticket early. That saved us the escalation. Thanks.” When feedback goes both ways, corrective feedback stops feeling scary.</li>
</ol>
<h2>Final note</h2>
<p>Feedback does not kill morale. Avoiding feedback kills morale.</p>
<p>The team wants a manager who sees the work and says something clear about it. Early, calm, specific. That is respect.</p>
<p>You are not being harsh. You are being useful.</p>
<p>This article is based on the Plain Act approach to early management pressure.</p>
<p>---</p>
    </article>

    {shorts.length > 0 && (
      <section class="shorts-section">
        <p class="kicker">Shorts</p>
        <h2>Short clips from this lesson</h2>
        <div class="shorts-grid">
          {shorts.map((short, index) => (
            <div class="short-frame">
              <iframe
                src={short.embed}
                title={`${title} short ${index + 1}`}
                loading="lazy"
                allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
                allowfullscreen
              ></iframe>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <section class="cta-box">
      <p class="kicker">Plain Act</p>
      <h2>The First 30 Days as a New Manager</h2>
      <p>A practical manual for first-time managers carrying authority, feedback, delegation, and decision pressure.</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Open the book page</a>
        <a href={articlesUrl}>Back to articles</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="related">
      <p class="kicker">Related</p>
      <div class="related-grid">
        {related.map((item) => (
          <a class="related-card" href={href(item.slug)}>
            <span>{item.topic}</span>
            <strong>{item.title}</strong>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article-page {
    max-width: 920px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2.6rem 1.2rem 4rem;
  }

  .crumbs {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.45rem;
    align-items: center;
    margin-bottom: 1.4rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .crumbs a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .article-hero {
    max-width: 780px;
  }

  .kicker {
    margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .article-hero h1 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(2.1rem, 5vw, 4.4rem);
    line-height: 0.96;
    letter-spacing: -0.06em;
  }

  .article-hero p {
    margin-top: 1rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 1.06rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  .hero-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.7rem;
    margin-top: 1.2rem;
  }

  .hero-actions a {
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 999px;
    padding: 0.55rem 0.82rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.035);
  }

  .media-block {
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .video-frame {
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    background: #05070a;
    box-shadow: 0 24px 70px rgba(0,0,0,.2);
  }

  .video-frame.long {
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;
  }

  .video-frame iframe,
  .short-frame iframe {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    border: 0;
  }

  .article-body {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    padding: 1.2rem 0;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(h1) {
    display: none;
  }

  .article-body :global(h2) {
    margin-top: 2.1rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
    font-size: clamp(1.35rem, 2.5vw, 2rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.035em;
  }

  .article-body :global(h3) {
    margin-top: 1.6rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(p),
  .article-body :global(li) {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.78;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(strong) {
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(blockquote) {
    margin: 1.2rem 0;
    padding: 1rem 1.1rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    color: var(--text);
    border-radius: .75rem;
  }

  .shorts-section,
  .cta-box,
  .related {
    margin-top: 2.2rem;
  }

  .shorts-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .short-frame {
    position: relative;
    aspect-ratio: 9 / 16;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: .9rem;
    background: #05070a;
  }

  .cta-box {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1.2rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    padding: 1.2rem;
  }

  .cta-box h2 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(1.45rem, 3vw, 2.4rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.04em;
  }

  .cta-box p {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .related-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .related-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: .45rem;
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
  }

  .related-card span {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: .75rem;
    letter-spacing: .12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .shorts-grid,
    .related-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
